For `blog/[id].js` → `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx`:
```tsx
export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts');
  const posts: Post[] = await res.json();
  return posts.slice(0, 10).map(post => ({ id: post.id.toString() }));
}

export async function generateMetadata({ params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { id } = await params;
  const res = await fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`);
  const post: Post = await res.json();
  return { title: `${post.title} - My Blog`, ... };
}

export default async function BlogPost({ params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const [postRes, commentsRes] = await Promise.all([
    fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`),
    fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}/comments`),
  ]);
  // ...
}
```

For the `loading.tsx` file - I should add one for the blog post route to replace the `router.isFallback` loading state:
`app/blog/[id]/loading.tsx`

For the API routes, let me think about the conversion:

`app/api/posts/route.ts`:
```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';

export async function GET() {
  const posts = [
    { id: 1, title: 'First Post', content: 'This is the first post' },
    { id: 2, title: 'Second Post', content: 'This is the second post' },
  ];
  return NextResponse.json(posts);
}

export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const body = await request.json();
  const { title, content } = body;

  if (!title || !content) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Title and content are required' }, { status: 400 });
  }

  const newPost = {
    id: Date.now(),
    title,
    content,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };

  return NextResponse.json(newPost, { status: 201 });
}
```

`app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts`:
```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';

type Params = Promise<{ id: string }>;

export async function GET(request: NextRequest, { params }: { params: Params }) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const post = {
    id: parseInt(id),
    title: `Post ${id}`,
    content: `This is the content for post ${id}`,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  return NextResponse.json(post);
}

export async function PUT(request: NextRequest, { params }: { params: Params }) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const body = await request.json();
  const { title, content } = body;

  const updatedPost = {
    id: parseInt(id),
    title: title || `Post ${id}`,
    content: content || `Updated content for post ${id}`,
    updatedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  return NextResponse.json(updatedPost);
}

export async function DELETE(request: NextRequest, { params }: { params: Params }) {
  const { id } = await params;
  return NextResponse.json({ message: `Post ${id} deleted successfully` });
}
```

Now for the `_error.js` → App Router equivalent. The original `_error.js` handles both client and server errors with a status code. In App Router:
- `app/error.tsx` is an error boundary that catches errors in the root segment
- `app/global-error.tsx` catches errors in the root layout itself

The original error page showed different messages based on status code. Since App Router error pages don't directly get the status code, I'll create a meaningful error page that works with the error object.

Let me also think about proper types. I'll create a `lib/types.ts` for shared types.

One more thing: the `AppProvider` uses `createContext` and `useState` - these are client-side features. In App Router, I need to add `'use client'` directive to the AppProvider.tsx since it uses React hooks.

Also, for the root `layout.tsx`, I need to import and wrap children with AppProvider, import global CSS, etc.

Let me also think about the Head component from `next/head`. In App Router, we use the Metadata API. For server components, we export a `metadata` object or `generateMetadata` function. In the layout, I can set default metadata and individual pages can override.

OK let me think about the layout.tsx more carefully:

```tsx
